3. echo "test" > fun = â€œtestâ€ is written in the file; there are 4 characters.
echo "another test" >> fun = I executed this command without deleting previous file named â€˜funâ€™. Therefore what I saw in the file named â€˜funâ€™ is â€œtestanother testâ€ and there are 16 characters including space.
wc -c fun = when I executed this command, there was not any change in the file named â€˜funâ€™. This command is used to count bytes of the related file. When I executed this command, I saw â€œ18 funâ€ on the command page.

4. By default, the echo command output ends with a newline character. However, if I want, I can change this behavior using the â€œ-nâ€ command line option. Here is the practice:
